('114', 'Defense', 'RIT House and 1 Zone', '["https://lacrosse.labradorsports.com/play?l=OLcwPEKD478uwo8j453A","https://lacrosse.labradorsports.com/play?l=an1W37412dYeVEbEzLc9","https://lacrosse.labradorsports.com/play?l=JvCpwg0ONqefTADHDSo6","https://lacrosse.labradorsports.com/play?l=Yz3YeXI9T0J6Kd5HC1rc","https://lacrosse.labradorsports.com/play?l=Ga1ttvpfmobVsE4N4pW9","https://lacrosse.labradorsports.com/play?l=j5ideji0Hm9URQLMKqJ9","https://lacrosse.labradorsports.com/play?l=lJC36CTAz34Zs8TmpiB1","https://lacrosse.labradorsports.com/play?l=LhGx2HOP3ZUCZ4WuWvlO","https://lacrosse.labradorsports.com/play?l=gesoRwiF2jMvPz5PkiSC","https://lacrosse.labradorsports.com/play?l=7xUvfMLTiigHysNPlXmT"]'::jsonb, 'RIT’s House and 1 Zone combines a House Man Down Defense with a single crease player inside. | As off ball players enter and exit the crease area - the tiger must let house players know that the player he is defending is moving off the crease. Likewise - perimeter players must communicate to the Tiger that a player is moving to the crease for them to cover. HOUSE Players must cover backside cutters until they know the Tiger has taken responsibility to cover them. | There are any options to play the ball at X depending on what you’d like to do with personnel. I don’t like the idea of leaving a player at X to look back up through the field - but you may want to hold the pipes.
